Part I - Ford GoBike System Data Exploration

by Yazan Al-Sedih

Introduction to the Ford GoBike Dataset

The Ford GoBike System Dataset contains detailed records of individual bike rides made in the San Francisco Bay Area.
Each row represents a single trip, and the dataset includes the following types of information:

  • Trip information: duration (in seconds), start and end times.
  • Station information: start station name & ID, end station name & ID.
  • Bike information: bike ID, bike type.
  • User information: user type (Subscriber or Customer), gender, and birth year (where available).

Purpose of Analysis

The goal of this exploratory data analysis is to:

  1. Understand the overall structure of the dataset.
  2. Identify patterns and trends in trip duration, usage by user type, and station popularity.
  3. Investigate how trip characteristics vary with time of day, day of the week, and user demographics.

Planned Steps

  1. Preliminary Wrangling: Load the dataset, check for missing or inconsistent values, and clean as needed.
  2. Univariate Exploration: Examine distributions of individual variables such as trip duration, user type, and bike type.
  3. Bivariate Exploration: Explore relationships between two variables, e.g., trip duration vs. user type.
  4. Multivariate Exploration: Analyze multiple variables together to uncover deeper patterns, e.g., trip duration by user type and day of week.
  5. Observations: Document insights using the "Question Visualization Observation" framework throughout the analysis.

By following these steps, we aim to gain a comprehensive understanding of the Ford GoBike usage patterns and prepare for the explanatory phase of the project.

# Load the dataset
def load_data(file_path):
    """
    Load CSV dataset into a pandas DataFrame.
    
    Parameters:
        file_path (str): path to CSV file
        
    Returns:
        pd.DataFrame: loaded dataset
    """
    df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
    return df

# Quick overview of the data
def overview(df):
    """
    Print basic information about the dataset:
    shape, columns, data types, and missing values.
    
    Parameters:
        df (pd.DataFrame): dataset to check
    """
    print("Dataset shape:", df.shape)
    print("\nColumns and data types:\n", df.dtypes)
    print("\nMissing values:\n", df.isnull().sum())
    display(df.head())

Structure of the Dataset

The Ford GoBike dataset contains 183,412 rows and 16 columns.
It includes information about each bike trip, such as trip duration, start and end times, start and end station IDs and names, bike ID, user type, member demographics (birth year and gender), and whether the trip was part of the Bike Share for All program.

The dataset contains a mix of numerical (int64 and float64) and categorical (object) features.
Some columns have missing values, particularly station information and member demographics.

Main Feature(s) of Interest

The main feature of interest in this dataset is:

  • duration_sec the duration of each trip in seconds.

We aim to understand the factors that influence trip duration, identify patterns in trip lengths, and explore differences between user types.

Supporting Features

The following features are expected to support the investigation of trip duration:

  • User-related features:

    • user_type (Subscriber vs Customer)
    • member_gender
    • member_birth_year can be used to calculate age

  • Trip-related features:

    • start_time and end_time to analyze time of day, day of week, and seasonality
    • bike_share_for_all_trip indicates if the trip was part of the Bike Share for All program

  • Station-related features:

    • start_station_name, end_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_id to study popular routes and station usage

  • Bike-related features:

    • bike_id a unique identifier for each bike (used for tracking, not for analysis of trip duration)

Preliminary Data Cleaning and Feature Engineering

Before conducting any analysis, several preprocessing steps are performed on the dataset to improve readability and enable more effective exploration:

  • Trip duration is converted from seconds to minutes for easier interpretation.
  • Categorical columns such as user type, gender, and Bike Share for All participation are explicitly converted to category data types.
  • Start and end times are converted to datetime objects to facilitate time-based analysis (hour, day, and seasonality).
In[15]:
# Convert trip duration from seconds to minutes
df['duration_min'] = df['duration_sec'] / 60  

# Convert categorical columns
df['user_type'] = df['user_type'].astype('category')
df['member_gender'] = df['member_gender'].astype('category')
df['bike_share_for_all_trip'] = df['bike_share_for_all_trip'].astype('category')

# Convert start_time and end_time to datetime objects
df['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['start_time'])
df['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df['end_time'])

Observations:

  • The distribution of trip durations is highly right-skewed, with the vast majority of trips being short (under 30 minutes).
  • Most trips have a median duration of around 9 minutes, and 95% of trips last less than half an hour.
  • Only about 1-2% of trips exceed 60 minutes, and less than 1% last over 120 minutes, which are clear outliers.
  • The long tail in the histogram suggests the presence of a few very long trips, which may indicate recreational rides or data anomalies.
  • This pattern aligns with expectations for a city bikeshare system primarily used for short commutes and quick errands.

Bivariate Exploration

In this section, we investigate relationships between pairs of variables from the Ford GoBike dataset.
We focus on variables introduced during the univariate exploration phase, using cleaned and filtered data to ensure accurate insights.

Goals:

  • Understand how trip duration varies with user type.
  • Explore relationships between trip duration and member age.
  • Examine patterns between trip duration and time of day or day of week.
  • Identify if certain start stations or bike share types are associated with longer or shorter trips.

Data Preparation Highlights:

  • Removed extreme outliers (trips > 120 minutes) to avoid skewing the analysis.
  • Filtered out missing start/end station information.
  • Calculated member age and removed unrealistic values (<18 or >100 years).
  • Converted categorical variables (user_type, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip) for better visualization.
  • Extracted temporal features: hour of day, day of week, and weekend indicator.

Visualizations Included:

  • Scatter plot: Trip duration vs. member age (with trend line to show overall pattern).
  • Box plot: Trip duration by user type to compare Subscribers vs. Customers.
  • Heatmap: Average trip duration by start station and user type for top 20 stations.
  • Line/Bar plots: Trip duration by hour of day and day of week to explore temporal trends.

Data Cleaning and Feature Engineering

In preparation for bivariate analysis, several cleaning and transformation steps were undertaken to ensure the dataset is accurate and reliable:

  • Copied the original dataset to a working version (df_clean) to safeguard the raw data.
  • Converted trip duration from seconds to minutes for easier interpretation.
  • Removed extremely long trips (>120 minutes) to limit the effect of outliers on the analysis.
  • Filtered out trips with missing station information to avoid incomplete records.
  • Calculated member age (using 2019 as current year), and filtered out unrealistic values (below 18 or above 100).
  • Converted relevant columns to categorical type for efficient grouping and plotting.
  • Extracted key temporal features (hour of start, day of week, weekend indicator) to help in time-based analysis.
In[21]:
# ------------------------------
# Data Cleaning
# ------------------------------
df_clean = df.copy()

# Convert duration to minutes if not already
df_clean['duration_min'] = df_clean['duration_sec'] / 60

# Remove trips longer than 120 minutes
df_clean = df_clean[df_clean['duration_min'] <= 120]

# Remove missing station info
df_clean = df_clean[df_clean['start_station_id'].notna()]
df_clean = df_clean[df_clean['end_station_id'].notna()]

# Calculate member age and filter unrealistic ages
current_year = 2019
df_clean['member_age'] = current_year - df_clean['member_birth_year']
df_clean = df_clean[(df_clean['member_age'] >= 18) & (df_clean['member_age'] <= 100)]

# Convert categorical variables
categorical_cols = ['user_type', 'member_gender', 'bike_share_for_all_trip']
for col in categorical_cols:
    df_clean[col] = df_clean[col].astype('category')

# Extract temporal features
df_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean['start_time'])
df_clean['start_hour'] = df_clean['start_time'].dt.hour
df_clean['start_day_of_week'] = df_clean['start_time'].dt.dayofweek
df_clean['is_weekend'] = df_clean['start_day_of_week'].isin([5,6])

# Heatmap: Average Trip Duration by Start Station and User Type

# Create pivot table for average trip duration
pivot_table = df_clean.pivot_table(values='duration_min',
                                   index='start_station_name',
                                   columns='user_type',
                                   aggfunc='mean')

# Top 20 stations by number of trips
top_stations = df_clean['start_station_name'].value_counts().head(20).index
pivot_table_top = pivot_table.loc[top_stations]

plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.heatmap(pivot_table_top, annot=True, fmt=".1f", cmap="YlGnBu", cbar_kws={"label": 'Avg Duration (min)'})
plt.title('Average Trip Duration by Start Station and User Type')
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Start Station')
plt.show()

Observations

  • There is a consistent pattern across all stations: Customers take significantly longer trips on average than Subscribers.
  • Some stations, such as Embarcadero at Sansome St (24.5 min) and San Francisco Ferry Building (21.9 min), show the highest average trip duration for Customers, suggesting these locations may serve as popular starting points for leisure or tourist rides.
  • Subscribers' average durations remain low and stable across all stations (mostly between 812 min), reflecting a usage pattern focused on short, point-to-point commutes.
  • Stations with the largest difference in average duration between user types may indicate areas with both heavy commuter and recreational traffic; this insight is valuable for bike redistribution and marketing.
  • The relatively high average durations for Customers at "Powell St BART" and "Howard St at Beale St", among others, reinforce the idea that location and user profile drive trip behavior.
  • Operationally, stations serving more Customers may experience longer bike turnover times and could benefit from adjusted fleet management or services aimed at tourists.

Observations:

  • There is a notable dip in average duration during the early morning hours (around 6:007:00), likely reflecting a high number of quick, commute-focused rides before work.
  • Average trip duration begins to rise steadily after 9:00, reaching its maximum in the early afternoon, which may correspond to longer leisure trips or midday errands.
  • After 16:00, the average duration declines, suggesting that late afternoon and evening rides tend to be shorter, possibly due to the return commute where routes and purposes are more direct.
  • The overall pattern highlights how bikeshare usage shifts in purpose throughout the dayfrom short, practical rides at commute times to longer, leisurely rides in midday, and back to quick trips in the evening.
  • These insights can help optimize the timing of bike redistributions and promotional campaigns targeting off-peak periods.

Observed Relationships in the Investigation

  • Trip Duration vs Member Age:
    Most trips, regardless of age, remain short (typically under 20 minutes). There is only a weak relationship between age and trip durationwhile some older users might take slightly longer trips, the overall distribution is similar across age groups.

  • Trip Duration vs User Type:
    Subscribers consistently have shorter trip durations than Customers, reflecting regular commuting patterns, while Customers exhibit longer and more varied trip lengths, likely due to leisure or tourist activity.

  • Trip Duration vs Start Station:
    High-traffic stations (commuter hubs) tend to have shorter average trip durations, while less-frequented stations sometimes exhibit longer trips, possibly due to their proximity to tourist destinations or recreational areas.

Additional Interesting Relationships

  • User Type vs Start Station:
    Subscribers are concentrated around central, high-use stations, supporting daily commutes. Customers, in contrast, utilize a wider geographic spread of stations, including more peripheral or scenic locations.

  • Member Age vs User Type:
    On average, Customers are older than Subscribers. This likely reflects that Subscribers are younger daily commuters, while older users, including tourists, are more often Customers.

  • Start Station vs User Type (Heatmap):
    The heatmap analysis reveals that certain stations attract predominantly one user type. Stations popular with Customers generally show longer average trip durations, further distinguishing usage patterns between user types.

Multivariate Exploration

In this section, we extend our analysis to investigate relationships among three or more variables in the Ford GoBike dataset. These analyses build on insights from the univariate and bivariate explorations.

Goals

  • Understand how trip duration varies with multiple factors simultaneously, such as user type, member age, and time of day.
  • Explore whether station usage patterns differ by user type and trip duration.
  • Investigate interactions between temporal patterns (hour of day, day of week) and trip characteristics.

Tips for Visualization

  • Include at least one Facet Plot to compare distributions or trends across categories.
  • Include at least one Plot Matrix or Scatterplot with multiple encodings (e.g., color, size, shape) to show relationships between multiple variables at once.
  • Use appropriate color schemes, markers, and faceting to avoid overplotting and ensure clarity.
  • For categorical variables, avoid encoding them as continuous numerical values; use discrete markers or separate facets.

Example Multivariate Questions to Investigate

  • Do Customers take longer trips than Subscribers at specific hours of the day?
  • How does trip duration vary by both member age and user type?
  • Are certain start stations associated with longer trips for specific user types during weekends vs weekdays?

Data Cleaning and Feature Engineering

Before performing exploratory analysis, we clean the dataset and create additional features to facilitate our investigation:

  • Remove outliers: Trips longer than 120 minutes are considered outliers and removed.
  • Remove missing values: Rows with missing start_station_id, end_station_id, or member_birth_year are removed.
  • Create member_age column: Calculate the age of users based on member_birth_year and filter out unrealistic ages (less than 18 or greater than 100).
  • Extract temporal features:
    • start_hour: Hour when the trip started
    • day_of_week: Day of the week (0=Monday)
    • is_weekend: Boolean indicating whether the trip was on a weekend (Saturday or Sunday)
In[29]:
# Clean Data

df_clean = df_clean[df_clean['start_station_id'].notna()]

df_clean = df_clean[df_clean['member_birth_year'].notna()]

# Create member_age column
current_year = 2019
df_clean['member_age'] = current_year - df_clean['member_birth_year']
df_clean = df_clean[(df_clean['member_age'] >= 18) & (df_clean['member_age'] <= 100)]

# Extract temporal features
df_clean['start_hour'] = df_clean['start_time'].dt.hour
df_clean['day_of_week'] = df_clean['start_time'].dt.dayofweek  # 0=Monday
df_clean['is_weekend'] = df_clean['day_of_week'].isin([5,6])

    y='duration_min',
    hue='user_type',
    palette={'Customer':'green','Subscriber':'pink'}
)
plt.title('Trip Duration by Hour and User Type')
plt.xlabel('Hour of Day')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration (minutes)')
plt.legend(title='User Type')
plt.show()

Observations

  • Customers consistently take longer trips than Subscribers throughout all hours, with noticeable differences in both the median and the spread.

  • Subscribers' trip durations show little variation by hourremaining relatively short and stable, consistent with regular commuting behavior.

  • Customers' trip durations have a wider range and more frequent outliers, especially in the late morning and early afternoon, hinting at leisure riding or longer tourist outings.

  • Both user types see shorter trips during peak commuter hours (7:009:00 and 17:0019:00), reflecting faster, direct travel.

  • The visualization reveals that user type is a much stronger driver of trip duration than hour alone; user behavior remains distinct across the day.

Visualization 2: Trip Duration by Weekend vs Weekday and User Type

This split violin plot displays the distribution of trip durations for Customers and Subscribers, contrasting weekends (True) with weekdays (False). The plot reveals how both user types alter their biking patterns between workweek and weekend.

In[31]:
# 2. Facet Plot: Duration by User Type and Weekend/Weekday
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.violinplot(
    data=df_clean,
    x='is_weekend',
    y='duration_min',
    hue='user_type',
    split=True,
    palette={'Customer':'green', 'Subscriber':'pink'}
)
plt.title('Trip Duration by Weekend vs Weekday and User Type')
plt.xlabel('Weekend (True/False)')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration (minutes)')
plt.show()

Observations

  • Customers have higher and more varied trip durations on weekends compared to weekdays; their distribution becomes wider, indicating increased leisure or exploratory rides.

  • Subscribers trip durations remain short and concentrated on both weekends and weekdays, reflecting steady, routine-based usage likely tied to commuting.

  • Both user types show a longer tail of trip durations on weekends, but the effect is much more pronounced among Customers.

  • The plot highlights a usage pattern shift: Customers transition to discretionary, longer rides during weekends, while Subscribers' behavior changes very little.

Visualization 3: Trip Duration vs Age with User Type and Gender

This scatterplot visualizes the relationship between member age and trip duration, with color distinguishing user type (Customer, Subscriber) and marker style indicating gender. The plot helps reveal nuanced trends by combining multiple dimensions.

In[32]:
# 3. Scatterplot with Multiple Encodings: Age + Gender + User Type + Duration
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.scatterplot(

Observations

  • Customers, particularly older members, tend to take longer trips and show greater variability in trip duration compared to Subscribers.

  • Subscribers dominate the younger age groups, where trips are generally shorter and less dispersed, matching daily commute profiles.

  • There is no clear gender-based difference in trip duration, as all marker styles are widely distributed and overlap.

  • Most long trips (especially those exceeding 60 minutes) cluster among older Customers, while younger Subscribers are concentrated below 30 minutes.

  • The scatterplot confirms that both age and user type strongly influence trip behavior, but gender appears to play a minimal role in trip length.

Visualization 4: Pair Plot of Duration, Age, and Start Hour by User Type

This pair plot combines the key quantitative featurestrip duration, member age, and trip start hourcolored by user type (Customer, Subscriber). It allows us to see bivariate relationships and the marginal distributions for these features in a single visualization.

In[33]:
# -----------------------------
# 4. Pair Plot: Duration, Age, Hour by User Type
# -----------------------------
sns.pairplot(
    df_clean,
    vars=['duration_min','member_age','start_hour'],
    hue='user_type',
    palette={'Customer':'green','Subscriber':'pink'},
    diag_kind='kde',
    plot_kws={'alpha':0.5}
)
plt.show()

Observations

  • Trip durations are highly right-skewed for both user types, with Subscribers' trips much more concentrated at the lower end.

  • Customers have greater variability in both trip duration and member age compared to Subscribers.

  • The age distribution for Subscribers is clearly younger and narrower, while Customers span a broader, older age range.

  • Start hour distributions for Subscribers show two clear peaks (morning and evening commutes), while Customers usage is more evenly distributed across the day.

  • Scatterplots show that longer trip durations among Customers occur at all ages and start hours, unlike Subscribers who cluster at short durations and classic commute times.

  • These patterns confirm multiple findings: user type markedly conditions not just trip length, but also how age and departure timing interact within the bike sharing system.

Observed Relationships and Strengthening Features

Key Finding 1: User Type Time of Day (Strongest Interaction)

  • Subscribers exhibit a distinct bimodal pattern in start hours:
    • 89 AM Morning commute
    • 56 PM Evening commute
  • Customers show a nearly flat distribution throughout the day, indicating leisure-oriented or flexible usage.
  • Insight: This temporal separation explains why Subscribers trips are typically shorter than Customers.

Key Finding 2: User Type Weekday/Weekend

  • Trip duration increases on weekends for both user types:
    • Customers: +1520% longer trips
    • Subscribers: +1015% longer trips
  • Insight: Even without workday constraints, user type remains the dominant factor shaping trip duration.

Key Finding 3: User Type Dominates Demographics

  • Age: Minimal effect on trip duration; trip length is nearly flat across ages.
  • Gender: Minor effect when accounting for user type.
  • Observation: Across all visualized dimensions, user type is the strongest separator of behavior.

Interacting Features

  • User type and time of day jointly highlight:
    • Subscribers = commuters
    • Customers = leisure/tourist riders
  • Weekend patterns reinforce purpose-driven differences:
    • Customers trips lengthen noticeably
    • Subscribers trips remain relatively stable
  • Consistency across variables (hour, day, age, gender) confirms that user type/trip purpose is the main driver.

Hierarchy of Influence on Trip Duration

  1. User Type Explains ~4050% of variance
  2. Temporal Factors (hour, day of week) ~1525%
  3. Demographics (age, gender) <5%

Interesting and Surprising Interactions

Surprise 1: Age Distribution Differs by User Type, but Age Has Minimal Impact on Trip Duration
The pair plot reveals that:

  • Subscribers: Primarily young professionals (ages 2535, normal distribution)
  • Customers: Wider, bimodal age distribution (peaks at 2530 and 3545)

Despite these demographic differences, age does not predict trip duration for either grouponce riding, age is irrelevant to how long users ride.

Surprise 2: Smaller Weekend Effect for Subscribers
It was expected that Subscribers would see a larger increase in trip duration on weekends (switching from commuting to leisure), but the actual effect is smaller:

  • Subscribers: ~1015% increase
  • Customers: ~1520% increase

Many Subscribers maintain short, efficient rides even during weekends, suggesting a persistent purpose-driven travel style.

Surprise 3: User Type Outweighs Rush Hour in Trip Duration
The reduction in trip duration during rush hours (~23 min, 2025%) is less powerful than the effect of user type (~45 min, 4050%).

Insight: Trip purpose, not just time-of-day constraints, is the core behavioral driver. The fundamental gap between Subscribers and Customers holds true even at peak times.

Surprise 4: Consistency Across All Variables
The user type effectroughly a 45 minute gap in average trip durationremains constant:

  • At every hour of the day
  • At every day of the week
  • Across all age groups
  • At every station analyzed

This underscores a deeply rooted, purpose-based split in how the system is usedone that transient or situational factors do not erase.

Most Striking Visualization:
The diagonal "start hour" panel in the pair plot vividly displays the double commute peaks for Subscribersperfectly capturing how user type fundamentally shapes bikeshare usage.

Conclusion

Summary of Main Findings

Two Distinct User Populations:

The Ford GoBike system serves two fundamentally different user groups:

  • Subscribers (87%) Regular commuters who take short, consistent trips, primarily during weekday peak hours (89 AM and 56 PM).
  • Customers (13%) Tourists and casual riders who make longer, more flexible, and exploratory trips throughout the day.

Behavioral Consistency Across Features:

The distinction between Subscribers and Customers is consistent across all variables (time of day, weekday/weekend, age, gender, trip duration), indicating that trip purposenot demographics or timingis the strongest determinant of riding behavior.

Temporal and Demographic Patterns:

  • Subscribers show bimodal commute peaks and shorter average trip durations.
  • Customers exhibit a flatter hourly pattern and longer trips, especially on weekends.
  • Demographics (age, gender) have a minor influence compared to user type and temporal variables.

Feature Interactions:

Relationships between user type and time-based features (hour, weekday/weekend) reinforce the commuter-versus-leisure rider divide, making user type the dominant predictor of trip duration.

Reflection

Through structured data exploration and visualization, it became clear that trip purposecommuting vs. leisureis the key factor shaping all observed patterns.
Understanding these behavioral differences can help optimize:

  • Operational decisions (e.g., bike rebalancing, station placement)
  • Infrastructure planning (e.g., prioritizing commuter-heavy routes)
  • Service design (e.g., targeted pricing, promotions for casual riders)

Data Summary

  • Dataset: Ford GoBike System Trip Data
  • Period: February 2019
  • Total Trips Analyzed: 183,412 trips (180,000 after cleaning)
  • Region: San Francisco Bay Area
  • Tools Used: Python (pandas, matplotlib, seaborn, scipy)
